Molecular weight or molecular mass refers to the mass of a molecule. It is calculated as the sum of the mass of each constituent atom multiplied by the number of atoms of that element in the molecular formula.

Rotatable bond is defined as any single non-ring bond, bounded to nonterminal heavy (i.e., non-hydrogen) atom.
The exact mass of an isotopic species is obtained by summing the masses of the individual isotopes of the molecule.

The monoisotopic mass is the sum of the masses of the atoms in a molecule using the unbound, ground-state, rest mass of the principal (most abundant) isotope for each element instead of the isotopic average mass.
The topological polar surface area (TPSA) of a molecule is defined as the surface sum over all polar atoms in a molecule.
A heavy atom is defined as any atom except hydrogen in a chemical structure.

Formal charge is the difference between the number of valence electrons of each atom and the number of electrons the atom is associated with. Formal charge assumes any shared electrons are equally shared between the two bonded atoms.

The complexity rating of a compound is a rough estimate of how complicated a structure is, seen from both the point of view of the elements contained and the displayed structural features including symmetry. This complexity rating is computed using the Bertz/Hendrickson/Ihlenfeldt formula.

Isotopte Atom Count is the number of isotopes that are not most abundant for the corresponding chemical elements.  Isotopes are variants of a chemical element which differ in neutron number.  For example, among three isotopes of carbon (i.e., C-12, C-13, and C-14), the isotope atom count considers the C-13 and C-14 atoms, because C-12 is the most abundant isotope of carbon.

StringWithMarkup.String: Pale greenish-yellow to yellowish-grey powder or granules, which may have a faint odour of burnt sugar

Section.Description: Physical description - color

Reference: Chase et al; Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences 14th ed. Mack Publ Co. Easton, PA p. 825 (1970)

StringWithMarkup.String: The color of /ferrous gluconate/ solution depends on pH; they are light yellow at pH 2, brown at pH 4.5, and green at pH 7. The iron rapidly oxidizes at higher pH.

Section.Description: The solubility of a substance is the amount of that substance that will dissolve in a given amount of solvent. The default solvent is water, if not indicated.

StringWithMarkup.String: Soluble with slight heating in water. Practically insoluble in ethanol

Reference: Sax, N.I. Dangerous Properties of Industrial Materials. 4th ed. New York: Van Nostrand Reinhold, 1975., p. 768
Osol, A. and J.E. Hoover, et al. (eds.). Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences. 15th ed. Easton, Pennsylvania: Mack Publishing Co., 1975., p. 776

StringWithMarkup.String: SOLUBILITY INCR BY ADDN OF CITRIC ACID OR CITRATE ION

Reference: Chase et al; Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences 14th ed. Mack Publ Co. Easton, PA p. 825 (1970)

StringWithMarkup.String: 1 gram dissolves in about 10 ml of water with slight heating and in 1.3 ml of water at 100 °C. It forms supersaturated solutions which are stable for a period of time.

Section.Description: Tendency of a material to resist change or decomposition due to internal reaction, or due to the action of air, heat, light, pressure, etc. (See also Stability and Reactivity section under Safety and Hazards)

Reference: O'Neil, M.J. (ed.). The Merck Index - An Encyclopedia of  Chemicals, Drugs, and Biologicals. 13th Edition, Whitehouse  Station, NJ:  Merck and Co., Inc., 2001., p. 716

StringWithMarkup.String: Aqueous solutions are stabilized by the addition of glucose.

Reference: Osol, A. and J.E. Hoover, et al. (eds.). Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences. 15th ed. Easton, Pennsylvania: Mack Publishing Co., 1975., p. 776

StringWithMarkup.String: Affected by light & ferrous ion slowly oxidizes on exposure to air.

Reference: Osol, A. and J.E. Hoover, et al. (eds.). Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences. 15th ed. Easton, Pennsylvania: Mack Publishing Co., 1975., p. 776

StringWithMarkup.String: Approx neutral solutions undergo rapid oxidation

Reference: Osol, A. and J.E. Hoover, et al. (eds.). Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences. 15th ed. Easton, Pennsylvania: Mack Publishing Co., 1975., p. 776

StringWithMarkup.String: Oxidation retarded and stability improved by buffering to pH of 3.5 to 4.5 with citrate buffer

Section.Description: The decomposition temperature of a substance is the temperature at which the substance chemically decomposes

Reference: Lewis, R.J. Sax's Dangerous Properties of Industrial Materials. 9th ed. Volumes 1-3. New York, NY: Van Nostrand Reinhold, 1996., p. 1644

StringWithMarkup.String: When heated to decomposition it emits acrid smoke and irritating fumes

Section.Description: Additional property information.

Reference: Osol, A. and J.E. Hoover, et al. (eds.). Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences. 15th ed. Easton, Pennsylvania: Mack Publishing Co., 1975., p. 776

StringWithMarkup.String: Ascorbic acid and aminoacetic acid cause dark coloration; with pyridoxine, green color produced.

Reference: O'Neil, M.J. (ed.). The Merck Index - An Encyclopedia of  Chemicals, Drugs, and Biologicals. 13th Edition, Whitehouse  Station, NJ:  Merck and Co., Inc., 2001., p. 716

StringWithMarkup.String: Yellowish-gray or pale greenish-yellow powder. Slight odor of caramel. Soluble in water; practically insoluble in alcohol. Aqueous solutions are stabilized by addition of glucose. /Dihydrate/

Reference: Chase et al; Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences 14th ed. Mack Publ Co. Easton, PA p. 825 (1970)

StringWithMarkup.String: Ferrous gluconate is affected by light and the ferrous iron slowly oxidizes to ferric on exposure to air.

Reference: Chase et al; Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences 14th ed. Mack Publ Co. Easton, PA p. 825 (1970)

StringWithMarkup.String: Approximately neutral solutions undergo rapid oxidation; oxidation is retarded and stability improved by buffering to a pH of 3.5 to 4.5 with citrate buffer. Glycerin also retards oxidation.

Reference: Aldrich; Catalog Handbook of Fine Chemicals. Aldirch Chemical Company, Inc., Milwaukee, WI p.1086 (2004)

StringWithMarkup.String: The melting point for D-gluconic acid, ferrous salt dihydrate (98%) is 188 °C, decomposes. The specific optical rotation is +6.7 deg at 25 °C (c=1, H2O). /Dihydrate/

Reference: Osol, A. and J.E. Hoover, et al. (eds.). Remington's Pharmaceutical Sciences. 15th ed. Easton, Pennsylvania: Mack Publishing Co., 1975., p. 776

StringWithMarkup.String: Sugar, glycerin, & many organic hydroxy acids hinder precipitation. In neutral solution, soluble carbonates, phosphates, & oxalates produce precipitation. /Ferrous salts/
